==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|wĕdʹ}}, {{IPA|/ˈwɛd/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-wed.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɛd|lang=en}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|weddian|lang=ang}}. Related to Scots {{term|wed||pledge|lang=sco}}.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|weds|wedding|wed|past2=wedded}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To perform the [[marriage]] ceremony for; to join in [[matrimony]].
#: ''The priest '''wed''' the couple.''
#* Milton
#*: And Adam, '''wedded''' to another Eve, / Shall live with her.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To take as one's [[spouse]].
#: ''She '''wed''' her first love.''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To take a spouse.
# {{context|figuratively|transitive|lang=en}} To [[join]] (more or less permanently)
#* Shakespeare
#*: Thou art '''wedded''' to calamity.
#* Tillotson
#*: Men are '''wedded''' to their lusts.
#* '''2008''', Bradley Simpson, ''Economists with Guns'', page 72:
#*: {{...}} the PPS paper proposed a political doctrine that '''wedded''' modernization theory to U.S. support for national security states {{...}}
# {{context|figurative|intransitive|lang=en}} To take to oneself and support; to [[espouse]].
#* Clarendon
#*: They positively and concernedly '''wedded''' his cause.

